      {
        "id": 267484,
        "name": "Elliot Smith",
        "username": "openthedoorhal",
        "avatar_template": "/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/o/b3f665/{size}.png",
        "created_at": "2025-05-04T23:11:31.334Z",
        "cooked": "<aside class=\"quote no-group\" data-username=\"Avitus\" data-post=\"2\" data-topic=\"68978\">\n<div class=\"title\">\n<div class=\"quote-controls\"></div>\n<img alt=\"\" width=\"24\" height=\"24\" src=\"https://community.signalusers.org/user_avatar/community.signalusers.org/avitus/48/34172_2.png\" class=\"avatar\"> Avitus:</div>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Keeping software current is an industry standard, not anything specific to Signal.</p>\n</blockquote>\n</aside>\n<p>It is a violation of the user‚Äôs human rights to be denied access to their data, however momentarily, at the whim of some remote bureaucrat or developer, regardless of however well-intentioned that bureaucrat or developer might be.</p>\n<p>To lock the user out of their locally stored data pending an update is indicative of a malicious or sadistic psychological disposition.  Signal should take every precaution to keep people with such psychology from working as either paid developers or as volunteer contributors in any capacity, whether as code contributors or even as forum mods and especially in triaging bug reports and feature suggestions.</p>\n<p>We can keep an application updated without locking the user out of their data.  If the app needs to be updated in order to maintain compatibility with updated services provided by a centralized server, then the server can absolutely decline to provide services to previous versions of the app without the need to brick these older versions pending their update.</p>\n<p>If the idea is for the Signal organization to be able to, at any given time, remotely brick every user‚Äôs app pending an update in order to protect the userbase against some hypothetical security vulnerabilities that might need to be patched, I would suggest that users should at the very least have the option to opt-out of this scheme, and ideally users should need to explicitly opt-in to this remote-bricking scheme.</p>\n<aside class=\"quote no-group quote-modified\" data-username=\"Avitus\" data-post=\"2\" data-topic=\"68978\">\n<div class=\"title\">\n<div class=\"quote-controls\"></div>\n<img alt=\"\" width=\"24\" height=\"24\" src=\"https://community.signalusers.org/user_avatar/community.signalusers.org/avitus/48/34172_2.png\" class=\"avatar\"> Avitus:</div>\n<blockquote>\n<p>If it can be resolved by updating to the newest version, [‚Ä¶] then it‚Äôs not ‚Äúbricked‚Äù.</p>\n</blockquote>\n</aside>\n<p>Unfortunately, some users (myself included) whose Signal app was bricked, experienced that the update failed.  There will always be scenarious in which an update fails.  So unfortunately, the issue could not be resolved, and we could not regain access to our personal data stored in Signal.</p>\n<aside class=\"quote no-group\" data-username=\"Avitus\" data-post=\"2\" data-topic=\"68978\">\n<div class=\"title\">\n<div class=\"quote-controls\"></div>\n<img alt=\"\" width=\"24\" height=\"24\" src=\"https://community.signalusers.org/user_avatar/community.signalusers.org/avitus/48/34172_2.png\" class=\"avatar\"> Avitus:</div>\n<blockquote>\n<p>It does. It‚Äôs in the category name. What you actually want is an update to the category description.</p>\n</blockquote>\n</aside>\n<p>What I actually want is a user interface that is clear and unambiguous and that does not contradict its self at every turn, as in this instance where the category description implicitly contradicts the category name.</p>",
