        "cooked": "<p>Just want to drop here, love the passion shown for the correct labeling of a category.</p>\n<p>The point was that Signal had assembled a team of designers at the time. As of then they had the final say over user facing things, while before that time those choices were in the hands of the Android and iOS teams (Greyson and Nora mostly). Since then, as soon as a user would comment something like ‚Äòthat one button is confusing, why did you make it like that?‚Äô we got a vague reply ‚ÄòI‚Äôll pass the feedback on to design‚Äô but never heard of it again.</p>\n<p>The lack of response frustrated me. In my mind the smallest enhancements (it would just take a few minutes to fix most of these things) were now almost all being left unresolved. So I collected that type of feedback into a new category hoping the design team would notice how much feedback was directed at their department, and hoping they would come to the forum and interact with us directly. They never did that (actually maybe once or twice). Same with the new translators (who are hired through some company), most of them never directly interact (but these days the translation quality is pretty good so there is not a lot of translation feedback anymore).</p>\n<p>I think the UI/UX category works fine. Even if the UI/UX feedback is often ignored by Signal, it‚Äôs there for some future and keeping it seperate mostly helps keep the more in dept feature requests categories clear of small design related issues.</p>\n<p>Signal used to accept pull requests on github, used to have discussion between translators to decide on structure of sentences, particualr words chosen, keepin erman and Dutch similar in wordin etc. And UI/UX feedback used to get resoled with a commit the next moring. That‚Äôs no longer how Signal is being developed.</p>\n<p>Maybe someone enjoys this little story of how Signal and this forum grew out to be.</p>",
